You don't say why you're on your ninth installation.  If it's because of
the above-mentioned slow performance in Windows programs, reinstalling
won't help.  If you're having some other problems, please describe them,
since the solution may or may not be a reinstallation with the caches
disabled.  Windows under OS/2 will be slower than Windows under DOS 
(assuming the same executables; the version of Windows included with the 
"full" OS/2 is more on a par with Windows under DOS because it was 
recompiled with a better compiler).  Except for program load times and 
graphics speed in "seamless" sessions, the difference should be fairly 
minor, though.  Program load times are slow, in part, because OS/2 has to 
load Windows every time it loads a program (assuming no other Windows 
programs are active).  There's a program called SEAMWIN that will load 
Windows at boot time, thus reducing this issue.  Load times will likely 
still be slow on an 8MB system because the computer will have to start 
swapping sooner than under DOS.  Video performance can be improved by 
switching to a full-screen session.  Do this by right-clicking on a 
program object, selecting the arrow next to "Open," then selecting 
"Settings."  Click on the "Session" tab and select "WIN-OS/2 full 
screen."  The next time you start the program, the WPS will disappear 
from view and be replaced by the Windows program running all by itself.  
(OS/2 programs will still be active, but they'll be hidden from view, 
since the Windows program will be given full control of the screen.)

