Tom@takdsign.demon.co.uk (Tom Kellett) writes:

>I've installed OS/2 2.1 for windows and so far I'm quite disappointed 
>with the performance of the Win/OS side of things, which I can only
>describe as "soggy".
>I have a 486 with 8meg, Dos 6.2 and Windows for Workgropes :)

What kind of video board are you using? The performance of Win-OS/2
really depends on your video card's drivers. Until last week, I used
a Cirrus Logic 5424-based card that was terribly slow in seamless
Windows. Then I upgraded to an ET4000/W32p-based card, and seamless
Windows is faster than full-screen Windows under DOS on the 5424!

Also, what other drivers are you loading? If you use 8MB of RAM, you
should probably stay away from HPFS, multimedia, and networks; all those
will sit in RAM and give little headroom for your Windows applications
before the swapping kicks in and kills the speed of your computer.

>Now to the nub of things;  I've noticed odd references to disabling 
>shadowing and casheing when installing but I hav'nt tried it yet, is it 
>likely to gain me any benefit or is there some other tweak to try ?

The manuals recommend turning off the shadow RAM and external cache RAM
when you install OS/2. After you have installed OS/2 and shut down
normally, you can re-enable the shadow RAM and cache and get much
better performance. Be sure you DO turn those back on, because Windows
and WinOS/2 performance need the speed improvement of the cache...



